abstract: >-
  A personal essay collection and structured knowledge graph mapping the three
  major Buddhist Abhidharma traditions (Theravāda, Sarvāstivāda, Yogācāra) onto
  contemporary frameworks in computational phenomenology — predictive processing,
  active inference, Global Workspace Theory, Parallel Distributed Processing, and
  related approaches. Comprises twelve essays (six themes × English + Japanese), a
  cross-tradition dharma comparison table (~130 dharmas across nine sheets), and
  a JSON-LD knowledge graph (~267 nodes, schema.org + custom vocabulary) with
  bilingual labels and Sanskrit / Pāli / Chinese philological alignment. An
  interactive 2D/3D viewer is provided. v0.2.0 adds Theme 6 (The 念 Collision)
  on how the single Chinese character 念 carries four incompatible Buddhist
  senses (sati / 無念 / 念仏 / modern mindfulness), with Chan / Zen and Pure
  Land traditions added to the graph. Developed in collaboration with the Claude
  language model (Anthropic) for synthesis, cross-tradition mapping, and graph
  encoding; the author retains responsibility for all claims.
